<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1437,289,962]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,218,289,314]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Notes</emphasis>
. The three new species below fit the original diagnosis of the genus (
<bibRefCitation author="Huber, B. A." box="[1048,1192,289,314]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" pagination="1 - 348" refId="ref37855" refString="Huber, B. A. (2000) New World pholcid spiders (Araneae: Pholcidae): a revision at generic level. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 254, 1 - 348. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 (2000) 254 &lt;0001: nwpsap&gt; 2.0. co; 2" type="journal article" year="2000">Huber 2000</bibRefCitation>
). The modified male cheliceral fangs seem to be a unique synapomorphy that unites the type species from 
<collectingCountry box="[1116,1226,325,350]" name="Colombia" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Colombia</collectingCountry>
with several other species from 
<collectingCountry box="[316,429,361,386]" name="Colombia" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[449,544,361,386]" name="Ecuador" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[563,617,362,385]" name="Peru" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Peru</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[637,722,361,386]" name="Bolivia" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[797,909,361,386]" name="Argentina" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Argentina</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Huber, B. A." box="[931,1079,361,386]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" pagination="1 - 348" refId="ref37855" refString="Huber, B. A. (2000) New World pholcid spiders (Araneae: Pholcidae): a revision at generic level. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 254, 1 - 348. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 (2000) 254 &lt;0001: nwpsap&gt; 2.0. co; 2" type="journal article" year="2000">Huber 2000</bibRefCitation>
). The new species share this modification and are thus likely close relatives of the type species. They are particularly similar in several respects to the Colombian 
<taxonomicName authority="Huber, 2000" authorityName="Huber" authorityYear="2000" box="[352,588,433,458]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Chibchea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="valle">
<emphasis box="[352,439,433,458]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">C. valle</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Huber, B. A." box="[446,588,433,458]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" pagination="1 - 348" refId="ref37855" refString="Huber, B. A. (2000) New World pholcid spiders (Araneae: Pholcidae): a revision at generic level. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 254, 1 - 348. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 (2000) 254 &lt;0001: nwpsap&gt; 2.0. co; 2" type="journal article" year="2000">Huber, 2000</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, a species that is only known from the male 
<typeStatus box="[1085,1187,433,458]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">holotype</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="42" pageNumber="43" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1437,289,962]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
Apart from two of the three species newly described below, the recent molecular phylogeny of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Eberle et al. 2018)" authorityName="Eberle" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Eberle" baseAuthorityYear="2018" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">
Pholcidae (
<bibRefCitation author="Eberle, J. &amp; Dimitrov, D. &amp; Valdez-Mondragon, A. &amp; Huber, B. A." box="[158,363,505,530]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" pagination="141" refId="ref37668" refString="Eberle, J., Dimitrov, D., Valdez-Mondragon, A. &amp; Huber, B. A. (2018) Microhabitat change drives diversification in pholcid spiders. BMC Evolutionary Biology, 18, 141. https: // doi. org / 10.1186 / s 12862 - 018 - 1244 - 8" type="journal article" year="2018">
Eberle 
<emphasis box="[241,297,505,530]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
included only two Chilean species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Huber" authorityYear="2000" box="[803,911,505,530]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Chibchea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[803,911,505,530]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Chibchea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that were tentatively identified as 
<taxonomicName authority="Huber, 2000" authorityName="Huber" authorityYear="2000" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Chibchea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mapuche">
<emphasis box="[1301,1436,505,530]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">C. mapuche</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Huber, B. A." box="[151,289,541,566]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" pagination="1 - 348" refId="ref37855" refString="Huber, B. A. (2000) New World pholcid spiders (Araneae: Pholcidae): a revision at generic level. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 254, 1 - 348. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 (2000) 254 &lt;0001: nwpsap&gt; 2.0. co; 2" type="journal article" year="2000">Huber, 2000</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Huber, 2000" authorityName="Huber" authorityYear="2000" box="[342,624,541,566]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Chibchea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="picunche">
<emphasis box="[342,475,541,566]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">C. picunche</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Huber, B. A." box="[482,624,541,566]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" pagination="1 - 348" refId="ref37855" refString="Huber, B. A. (2000) New World pholcid spiders (Araneae: Pholcidae): a revision at generic level. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 254, 1 - 348. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 (2000) 254 &lt;0001: nwpsap&gt; 2.0. co; 2" type="journal article" year="2000">Huber, 2000</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. Both lack modifications of the male cheliceral fangs, and they were thus explicitly assigned tentatively to the genus in 
<bibRefCitation author="Huber, B. A." box="[682,840,577,602]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" pagination="1 - 348" refId="ref37855" refString="Huber, B. A. (2000) New World pholcid spiders (Araneae: Pholcidae): a revision at generic level. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 254, 1 - 348. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 (2000) 254 &lt;0001: nwpsap&gt; 2.0. co; 2" type="journal article" year="2000">Huber (2000)</bibRefCitation>
. The molecular phylogeny does not recover a close relationship between these Chilean species and the species newly described below, suggesting that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Huber" authorityYear="2000" box="[1265,1373,613,638]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Chibchea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1265,1373,613,638]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Chibchea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in its current scope is polyphyletic. In an ongoing molecular study (L.S. Carvalho 
<emphasis box="[1038,1097,649,674]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">et al.</emphasis>
, unpubl. data), the three new species described below form a monophyletic group with two undescribed Andean species that also have modified male cheliceral fangs (“L17-168” from 
<collectingRegion box="[598,675,722,745]" country="Peru" name="Loreto" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Loreto</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[687,742,722,745]" name="Peru" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Peru</collectingCountry>
; and “L17-230” from 
<collectingRegion box="[992,1072,722,745]" country="Bolivia" name="La Paz" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">La Paz</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1084,1171,721,746]" name="Bolivia" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Bolivia</collectingCountry>
), further supporting the conclusion that this clade represents ‘true’ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Huber" authorityYear="2000" box="[629,736,757,782]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Chibchea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[629,736,757,782]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Chibchea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
even though we have no molecular data from the 
<typeStatus box="[1293,1341,758,782]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">type</typeStatus>
species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1437,289,962]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
The recent molecular phylogeny of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Eberle et al. 2018)" authorityName="Eberle" authorityYear="2018" baseAuthorityName="Eberle" baseAuthorityYear="2018" box="[612,958,793,818]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">
Pholcidae (
<bibRefCitation author="Eberle, J. &amp; Dimitrov, D. &amp; Valdez-Mondragon, A. &amp; Huber, B. A." box="[740,950,793,818]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" pagination="141" refId="ref37668" refString="Eberle, J., Dimitrov, D., Valdez-Mondragon, A. &amp; Huber, B. A. (2018) Microhabitat change drives diversification in pholcid spiders. BMC Evolutionary Biology, 18, 141. https: // doi. org / 10.1186 / s 12862 - 018 - 1244 - 8" type="journal article" year="2018">
Eberle 
<emphasis box="[824,883,793,818]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">et al.</emphasis>
2018
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
places the genus in a very basal position among 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Simon" authorityYear="1893" box="[237,385,829,854]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Modisiminae">Modisiminae</taxonomicName>
but support values for these basal nodes are very low and the sister group of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Huber" authorityYear="2000" box="[1300,1407,829,854]" class="Arachnida" family="Pholcidae" genus="Chibchea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1300,1407,829,854]" italics="true" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">Chibchea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is therefore essentially unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="42.[151,1437,289,962]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43">
The genus was originally thought to have an Andean distribution (
<bibRefCitation author="Huber, B. A." box="[949,1090,901,926]" pageId="42" pageNumber="43" pagination="1 - 348" refId="ref37855" refString="Huber, B. A. (2000) New World pholcid spiders (Araneae: Pholcidae): a revision at generic level. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 254, 1 - 348. https: // doi. org / 10.1206 / 0003 - 0090 (2000) 254 &lt;0001: nwpsap&gt; 2.0. co; 2" type="journal article" year="2000">Huber 2000</bibRefCitation>
). The three new species below extend the distribution to include large parts of the Amazon basin.
</paragraph>
